@article{Linsley1958,
abstract = {—As part of a long-range program on the hydrology of small watersheds, a corre­ lation between the two-year, one-hour rainfall intensity at 126 recording rainfall stations in northern California and related topographic and climatic parameters has been made. The re­ sulting correlation has a coefficient of correlation of 0.88 and a standard error of 0.067 inch/ hour. With this relation, it is possible to show the variation of rainfall intensity over the area in much greater detail than has hitherto been possible from observed intensity data alone. This paper discusses the parameters employed, the methods of correlation, and the results obtained. Introduction—One of the problems in any study of rainfall intensity is the limited number of stations with record suitable for frequency analy­ sis. For a regional study, data are limited to the hydrologic network stations available since about 1940. After preliminary study, it was decided to limit this analysis to California north of 35° N to avoid introducing large scale climatic factors. In this area approximately 150 station records were available for use. After screening to eliminate records which were too short or were composites from several station locations the number was reduced to 126. The maximum length of record was ten years and the average length substantially less. Conse­ quently the two-year, one hour intensity was adopted as the best choice of a dependent param­ eter. Since clock-hour data were readily avail­ able, these were used although the maximum 60-min values would be somewhat higher. Occasional summer thunderstdrms produce high-intensity rains in California. Because these storms are the result of quite different meterological processes, they were excluded from the analysis by using only the September through April period. Since most of these summer rains fall on dry ground and pro­ duce little runoff, this exclusion does not seem to affect the utility of the results. The general technique utilized is that previously employed by Spreen [1947] Burns [1952], and others for relating mean annual or mean seasonal pre­ cipitation to topography. The coaxial method of graphical correlation [Linsley and others, 1949] was employed because of the flexibility it offers. Since a relatively large number of stations was to be analyzed, data were transcribed onto Key sort punched cards. These cards could be easily strati­ fied and average values computed for each pa­ rameter as needed. The complete study [Linsley, 1956] involved comparison of four alternative relationships. This paper reports only the one which seems to offer the best results. Index daily rainfall—It is a logical assumption that, within a small region where the occurrence of rainfall at all stations is limited to about the same number of hours in a year, hourly intensities will bear some relation to mean annual precipita­ tion. The study area is too large for strict adherence to this assumption and a parameter called index daily rainfall was defined by},
